---
import PageShell from '../../../../components/PageShell.astro';
import CTABox from '../../../../components/CTABox.astro';
import ComparisonTable from '../../../../components/ComparisonTable.astro';

const tocItems = [
  { id: 'overview', text: 'Overview', level: 2 },
  { id: 'why-france', text: 'Why Retirees Choose France', level: 2 },
  { id: 'visa-options', text: 'Visa Options for Retirees', level: 2 },
  { id: 'insurance-requirements', text: 'Insurance Requirements', level: 2 },
  { id: 'recommended-providers', text: 'Recommended Providers', level: 2 },
  { id: 'healthcare-access', text: 'Healthcare Access', level: 2 },
  { id: 'costs', text: 'Cost Planning', level: 2 },
  { id: 'faqs', text: 'Common Questions', level: 2 },
];

const relatedLinks = [
  { title: 'France Insurance Guide', href: '/countries/france/insurance' },
  { title: 'Long-Stay Visa Guide', href: '/visas/retirement-visa/in/france' },
  { title: 'Senior Insurance', href: '/best/senior-insurance' },
  { title: 'Pre-Existing Conditions', href: '/best/pre-existing-conditions-insurance' },
  { title: 'Portugal for Retirees', href: '/insurance-for/retirees/in/portugal' },
];

const providerColumns = [
  { key: 'provider', header: 'Provider' },
  { key: 'ageLimit', header: 'Max Entry Age' },
  { key: 'preExisting', header: 'Pre-Existing' },
  { key: 'franceNetwork', header: 'France Network' },
  { key: 'monthly', header: 'Monthly (Age 60)' },
];

const providerRows = [
  { provider: 'Cigna Global', ageLimit: '74', preExisting: 'Covered (24mo wait)', franceNetwork: 'Excellent', monthly: '$380-550' },
  { provider: 'Allianz Care', ageLimit: '74', preExisting: 'Moratorium option', franceNetwork: 'Excellent', monthly: '$340-500' },
  { provider: 'AXA Global', ageLimit: '70', preExisting: 'Case-by-case', franceNetwork: 'Excellent (French HQ)', monthly: '$360-520' },
  { provider: 'Bupa Global', ageLimit: '65 (new)', preExisting: 'Full underwriting', franceNetwork: 'Excellent', monthly: '$400-580' },
];

const costColumns = [
  { key: 'item', header: 'Expense' },
  { key: 'monthly', header: 'Monthly' },
  { key: 'notes', header: 'Notes' },
];

const costRows = [
  { item: 'International Insurance (55-59)', monthly: '$320-450', notes: 'Comprehensive coverage' },
  { item: 'International Insurance (60-64)', monthly: '$380-550', notes: 'Comprehensive coverage' },
  { item: 'International Insurance (65-69)', monthly: '$480-700', notes: 'Comprehensive coverage' },
  { item: 'Sécurité Sociale + Mutuelle', monthly: '€100-200', notes: 'After PUMA enrollment' },
  { item: 'Private French Insurance', monthly: '€200-400', notes: 'France-only coverage' },
];
---

<PageShell
  title="Health Insurance for Retirees in France | Visa Guide 2026"
  description="Complete guide to health insurance for retirees moving to France. Long-stay visa requirements, Sécurité Sociale access, costs, and healthcare options for American and British retirees."
  headline="Health Insurance for Retirees in France"
  subheadline="France offers world-class healthcare, exceptional quality of life, and a clear path to residency. Here's how to navigate the insurance requirements—and access one of Europe's best health systems."
  heroImage="/images/countries/france-hero-bg.png"
  tocItems={tocItems}
  relatedLinks={relatedLinks}
  ctaButtonText="Get Retiree Quotes"
  ctaButtonHref="/go/cigna"
>
  <p class="text-sm text-neutral-500 mb-4">
    <strong>Affiliate disclosure:</strong> We may earn a commission when you click our links and purchase insurance. This doesn't affect our recommendations or the price you pay.
  </p>

  <h2 id="overview" class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4">Overview</h2>

  <p class="mb-4">
    France consistently ranks among the world's best healthcare systems—and for retirees, it's surprisingly accessible. The long-stay visa provides a pathway to residency, and after establishing yourself, the French system (Sécurité Sociale) covers everyone.
  </p>

  <p class="mb-4">
    This guide covers what retirees need to know: visa options, insurance for the application process, what comprehensive coverage costs, and how to transition to the French public system once you're established.
  </p>

  <div class="bg-primary-50 border border-primary-200 rounded-lg p-6 mb-8">
    <h3 class="font-bold text-lg mb-3">Key Facts for Retirees</h3>
    <ul class="space-y-2">
      <li><strong>Visa:</strong> Long-stay visa (VLS-TS) leading to carte de séjour</li>
      <li><strong>Insurance required:</strong> Yes, for visa application</li>
      <li><strong>Public healthcare:</strong> PUMA covers all legal residents</li>
      <li><strong>Cost of living:</strong> 25-40% lower than major US cities (varies by region)</li>
      <li><strong>Language:</strong> French proficiency helpful; English limited outside Paris</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <h2 id="why-france" class="text-2xl font-bold mt-12 mb-4">Why Retirees Choose France</h2>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">World-Class Healthcare</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    France's healthcare system regularly tops global rankings. Once enrolled in Sécurité Sociale, you access the same care as French citizens—at a fraction of US costs. Hospitals are excellent, specialists abundant, and wait times reasonable. The system covers roughly 70% of costs; supplemental insurance (mutuelle) handles the rest.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Quality of Life</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    From Provence lavender fields to Brittany coastlines, France offers diverse retirement lifestyles. Fresh markets, walkable towns, excellent public transport, and a culture that prioritizes life over work. Wine country, Mediterranean beaches, alpine villages, or cosmopolitan Paris—the choice depends on your preferences.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Geographic Advantages</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    Central European location means easy travel to neighboring countries. High-speed trains connect Paris to London (2h15), Amsterdam (3h), and Barcelona (6h). Mediterranean coast for summer, Alps for winter. Africa and the Middle East are short flights away.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Established Expat Communities</h3>
  <p class="mb-6">
    British and American retirees have settled in France for decades. The Dordogne, Provence, and Languedoc have significant English-speaking communities. Finding English-speaking services is possible, though learning French will significantly improve your experience.
  </p>

  <h2 id="visa-options" class="text-2xl font-bold mt-12 mb-4">Visa Options for Retirees</h2>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Long-Stay Visa (VLS-TS)</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    The standard path for retirees is the long-stay visa (visa de long séjour valant titre de séjour), specifically the "visitor" category. This grants 12 months initially and converts to a carte de séjour (residence permit) upon arrival. You must prove sufficient income to support yourself without working.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Income Requirements</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    France requires approximately €1,500/month minimum (SMIC level) for a single person, more for couples. Pension income, Social Security, investment returns, and rental income all qualify. You'll need bank statements showing stable income over several months.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Insurance Requirement</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    The visa application requires proof of comprehensive health insurance valid in France for the initial period. Travel insurance typically doesn't qualify—you need genuine health coverage. International health insurance from major providers meets this requirement.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Timeline</h3>
  <p class="mb-6">
    Apply at your local French consulate 2-3 months before planned move. Processing takes 2-8 weeks depending on consulate. After arrival, you have 3 months to validate your visa online through the ANEF portal. PUMA enrollment can begin after 3 months of stable residence.
  </p>

  <CTABox
    title="Need Visa Insurance for France?"
    description="Get coverage that meets French visa requirements. Quotes in minutes."
    buttonText="Get France Visa Quotes"
    buttonHref="/go/cigna"
  />

  <h2 id="insurance-requirements" class="text-2xl font-bold mt-12 mb-4">Insurance Requirements</h2>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">For Visa Application</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    Your insurance must cover France for the duration of your visa period. Documentation should clearly show: policyholder name, coverage territory including France, policy dates, and confirmation of health coverage (not just travel assistance). International health insurance from Cigna, Allianz, AXA, or similar providers meets requirements.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">What to Look For</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    For retirees, comprehensive coverage matters beyond visa compliance. Prioritize: inpatient and outpatient coverage, emergency evacuation (useful for trips outside France), pre-existing condition coverage, and direct billing with French hospitals. France has excellent hospitals, but international insurance gives you flexibility and fast access.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Pre-Existing Conditions</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    If you have existing health conditions, coverage options vary. Cigna offers guaranteed acceptance with 24-month waiting period for pre-existing conditions. Allianz offers moratorium underwriting—conditions excluded initially, covered after 2 years symptom-free. AXA (French-headquartered) reviews case-by-case.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">After PUMA Enrollment</h3>
  <p class="mb-6">
    Once enrolled in PUMA (Protection Universelle Maladie), you're covered by the French system. Most retirees then add a mutuelle (supplemental insurance) to cover the 30% co-pay. Some keep international coverage for travel or private care options; others rely entirely on the French system.
  </p>

  <h2 id="recommended-providers" class="text-2xl font-bold mt-12 mb-4">Recommended Providers</h2>

  <ComparisonTable columns={providerColumns} rows={providerRows} />

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-3">Cigna Global — Best Overall</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    Strong network across France with direct billing at major hospitals. Accepts applicants up to age 74. Guaranteed acceptance option means pre-existing conditions are covered after 24-month waiting period. Worldwide coverage for travel. Solid choice for retirees wanting comprehensive protection.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">AXA Global — French Heritage</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    French-headquartered insurer with extensive local networks. Particularly strong relationships with French hospitals. Familiar to French authorities—visa applications go smoothly. Good option for those planning to stay primarily in France.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Allianz Care — European Focus</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    German-headquartered with excellent European coverage. Moratorium underwriting can help with pre-existing conditions. Competitive pricing. Strong choice for those splitting time between France and other European countries.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">French Mutuelle Options</h3>
  <p class="mb-6">
    After PUMA enrollment, local mutuelles (MGEN, Harmonie, AG2R La Mondiale) offer supplemental coverage at €100-200/month. These cover the 30% co-pay plus extras like dental and optical. Age limits and acceptance criteria vary—shop around once you're established.
  </p>

  <CTABox
    title="Compare Retiree Insurance Options"
    description="See actual costs for your age and situation. No obligation quotes."
    buttonText="Get Personalized Quotes"
    buttonHref="/go/cigna"
  />

  <h2 id="healthcare-access" class="text-2xl font-bold mt-12 mb-4">Healthcare Access in France</h2>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Public Healthcare (Sécurité Sociale)</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    The French system covers everyone legally resident. PUMA enrollment is automatic after 3 months of stable residence. The system covers approximately 70% of costs; you pay the ticket modérateur (30% co-pay). A mutuelle covers this remainder plus additional services.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">How It Works</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    You receive a Carte Vitale (health card) after enrollment. Present it at doctors, pharmacies, and hospitals. The system reimburses automatically—often within days. For hospital stays, costs are typically settled directly between hospital and insurance. Out-of-pocket expenses are manageable.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Quality of Care</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    French hospitals range from adequate to world-class. Paris hospitals like Pitié-Salpêtrière and Georges Pompidou are internationally renowned. Regional hospitals are generally good. GP availability varies—some areas have shortages. Specialists are abundant in cities.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Language Considerations</h3>
  <p class="mb-6">
    Medical French is specialized vocabulary most English speakers won't know. In Paris and major tourist areas, finding English-speaking doctors is possible. In rural France, it's challenging. Consider learning medical French basics or having translation support available.
  </p>

  <h2 id="costs" class="text-2xl font-bold mt-12 mb-4">Cost Planning</h2>

  <ComparisonTable columns={costColumns} rows={costRows} />

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-3">Total Healthcare Budget</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    For a 60-year-old retiree: international insurance ($380-550/month) for the first year. After PUMA enrollment: Sécurité Sociale (free with PUMA) plus mutuelle (€100-200/month) plus occasional out-of-pocket (€50-100/month). Total post-PUMA: €150-300/month for comprehensive coverage.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Cost-Saving Strategies</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    <strong>Transition quickly:</strong> Get PUMA enrollment started as soon as eligible—it's free and comprehensive. <strong>Choose mutuelle wisely:</strong> Higher-tier mutuelles cost more but cover dental, optical, and alternatives. <strong>Use French generics:</strong> Pharmacies substitute generics automatically, saving significantly.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Compare to US Costs</h3>
  <p class="mb-6">
    Pre-Medicare US coverage at age 60-65 runs $1,000-1,800/month. Post-PUMA French coverage at €150-300/month represents 80-90% savings. Even during the international insurance period, costs are comparable to US coverage with better worldwide protection.
  </p>

  <h2 id="faqs" class="text-2xl font-bold mt-12 mb-4">Common Questions</h2>

  <div class="space-y-6 mb-8">
    <div class="border-b pb-4">
      <h3 class="font-semibold mb-2">How long until I can access French healthcare?</h3>
      <p>PUMA enrollment requires 3 months of stable, legal residence. Processing the Carte Vitale takes 2-4 additional weeks. Budget 4-5 months from arrival to full system access. International insurance covers you until then.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="border-b pb-4">
      <h3 class="font-semibold mb-2">Do I need to speak French?</h3>
      <p>For daily life and healthcare, French proficiency makes a significant difference. In Paris and major cities, English-speaking doctors exist but aren't guaranteed. In rural areas, French is essential. Consider language classes before or after moving.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="border-b pb-4">
      <h3 class="font-semibold mb-2">Can I get coverage with pre-existing conditions?</h3>
      <p>Yes. International insurers offer various options: Cigna's guaranteed acceptance with waiting period, Allianz's moratorium underwriting, case-by-case review from others. Once in PUMA, all conditions are covered by the French system—no exclusions.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="border-b pb-4">
      <h3 class="font-semibold mb-2">What's a mutuelle and do I need one?</h3>
      <p>A mutuelle is supplemental insurance covering the 30% co-pay Sécurité Sociale doesn't pay. Most French residents have one. Costs €100-200/month. Not legally required but practically essential—hospital stays without mutuelle coverage get expensive.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="border-b pb-4">
      <h3 class="font-semibold mb-2">Can I use my French coverage when traveling?</h3>
      <p>Sécurité Sociale provides limited coverage within the EU via the EHIC/GHIC card. Outside Europe, coverage is minimal. Many retirees keep travel insurance or international coverage for extended trips—especially if returning to the US regularly.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="border-b pb-4">
      <h3 class="font-semibold mb-2">What if I'm over 70?</h3>
      <p>International insurance options narrow after 70. Cigna accepts up to 74. AXA accepts up to 70 for new applicants. After that, focus on getting to France quickly and enrolling in PUMA—the French system has no age limits or exclusions once you're resident.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <CTABox
    title="Ready to Retire in France?"
    description="Get insurance that meets visa requirements and covers you until PUMA enrollment."
    buttonText="Get Your France Quotes"
    buttonHref="/go/cigna"
  />

  <p class="text-sm text-neutral-500 mt-12">
    This information is for educational purposes. Visa requirements, insurance options, and healthcare access rules change. Verify current requirements with French consulates. Consider consulting with an immigration specialist and insurance broker for your specific situation. Last updated: May 2026.
  </p>
</PageShell>
